<user_name>Swire Ho</user_name>< Review>
Very cool hike.  We went around Nov so it was nice.  There is no shades on the entire trail so it will be really hot in the summer. The lost horse mine is fence up so you can't go inside of the mine. Since this is one of the longer trail in the park so there aren't too many people.   Parking is very limited and a restroom(no water) is available at the trailhead.<//Review>

<Rating>2<//Rating>< Review>
Remarkably underwhelming. There is very little that makes up this abandoned mine, and the one building that might be considered interesting is behind a chain link fence. We were very disappointed after hiking two miles to get there.

The hike out here is equally underwhelming. Not much to see on the hike in except a vast empty expanse full with low shrubs. Very few Joshua Trees on the way.

It was nice to take a long hike, but I‚Äôm sure if we had looked a bit harder we would have found something much more interesting.</Review>

101924119546927055915<//user_id>
<response>None<//response><GmapID>0x80858738359f2f35:0x5239a83536f6e5a9</GmapID>< text>
Really can't beat $10.99 for an Indian lunch buffet! Their warm milky chai tea (from a coffee dispenser) is included, already sweetened to perfection.

We came on a Wednesday shortly after they opened for lunch and there were a couple tables of people seated. Naan is not served on the bar, they were still making it at the time and then the hot and fluffy naan was brought to our table after. The bar was not as extensive as Copper Chimney in SSF but it had a good selection at a better price. Some items on the bar include: veggie and chicken pakora, saag paneer, goat curry, coconut chicken curry (i think?), a few different vegetable curries, tandoori chicken, basmati rice, lentil soup, salad with toppings and dressing, rice pudding. I enjoyed the tandoori chicken and one of the yellow vegetable curries with cauliflower and squash. Saag paneer is one of my favorite Indian dishes and I don't know what is authentic but the saag here tasted especially herby, which I did not like at all.

Definitely worth checking out, I think they have a decent selection at an unbeatable price but in terms of food, we preferred other Indian spots that we've been to.< /text>

Most importantly, the CUSTOMER SERVICE WAS EXCELLENT! We were waiting for our friend outside after finishing dinner, and it was too cold so we asked whether we could wait inside. They were super nice and asked us whether we wanted something to drink. If u wanna try Indian food, this place is definitely recommended!<//review>

<pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>

<userid>101789640317906613804< /userid>< rating>
4</rating>
<time>1500601480405< /time>< Review>
We come here for the buffet. We are vegetarians and there are plenty of options to get us nice and full for a low price. The food is very tasty, especially the korma. There is enough salad and veggies for people like me who want to eat healthy, but also on occasion love warm, tasty, authentic Indian food. They usually have an eggplant dish, a kidney beans or lentils dish, a potatoes or broccoli dish, veggie pakora, and daal soup.. to name a few vegetarian options. The garlic naan comes with the buffet upon request as well, other Indian buffets will charge extra, so that is nice of them. The staff is always nice and friendly and remembers you even if it's been months since your last visit. This is also one of the only Indian dinner buffets in the city, so that is much appreciated when we are craving Indian food!< /Review>

< text>
Disappointed in Star India. I was hoping to find a local Indian place near my apartment for those nights I crave Chicken Tikka Masala and garlic naan (it's one of my guilty Star India disappointed me. My garlic naan has no garlic in sight... did they later on a garlic puree or use garlic powder? I can't tell. I usually like my garlic naans with pieces of garlic floating around, that true toasty-garlic taste. And my chicken tikka masala? Very loose in consistency, and no flavor. The pieces of chicken were generous, but Indian food without flavor might as well be frozen food (even Trader Joe's frozen chicken tikka masala and garlic naan are better than this).</text>

<user>112821674756732247951< /user>< username>
Isaiah Garcia< /username>
< Time>
1499135422928</Time>
< rating>
4</rating>
<text>I've been to most, if not all, Indian restaurants in San Francisco, and I can confidently assert that this is the greatest Indian buffet spot in town in regards to value! I'm a vegetarian, and I can proudly vouch for all the vegetarian dishes they serve here, save for the saag paneer, but that's just because I don't really like that to begin with. The chana masala is divine and is what primarily consumes my plate estate when I dine in. They also serve varying dishes containing potato which are delicious too. Of course, they have plenty of dishes with meat for you carnivores out there, which my family and friends praise highly too. (Chicken tikka masala is always available, don't worry!) They have lentil soup, salad, pakora (both vegetarian and chicken), and even dessert available for buffet. The waiters are always extremely attentive, and every time I'm about to ask for more water, they're already on their way, pitcher in hand and a smile on their face. There's never any pressure to leave regardless of how long you've been there, so feel free to come in and enjoy a nice, long, healthy feast in a restaurant filled with a caring staff and casual ambiance!<//text><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None</Resp>

< Review>
Pier 39 is very touristy. It's very, very touristy. But it is one of the most visited destinations in San Francisco. It has two levels of dining, shops, and attractions. It also offers an incredible view of the bay - if it isn't foggy, you can see the Golden Gate and Bay Bridges as well as Alcatraz Island! I managed to snap a couple of really good pictures of Alcatraz - but it was too foggy for the bridges while I was there. The walk along the pier is really nice and I highly recommend it if the day is nice.<//Review>

<Review>A Unique Craft Cocktail Bar. The Library Bar is not great with classic recipes but they are adapt at free forming bespoke drinks based on what you like. Of course experimentation doesn't always produce a hit, but fear not. The mixologists there will tweak your drink to bring the balance that suits you. They have more fresh vegetables, fruit and herbs than any bar I've seen. The thing that I love about them is that their cocktails are not something you'll find elsewhere. They are unique. It's a small joint so don't plan on bringing your top twenty friends for a drink. Be sure and check the hours too. Enjoy!<//Review>< Time>

< review>
Man oh man let me start by saying these people got it going on.  Family owned business and they got it together.  Not only are they opened during covid but there food is on point. Had a craving for chicharon yelped it and found this place luckily 8 miles from where we were and we headed there.  We were only going to get chicharon but the nice young man in the front said you want anything else, gave some suggestions and ended up getting chicharon,carnitas, buche and cueritos oh and a dozen of home made tortillas.  The food was phenomenal!!! We were set for the ride back home and dinner.  Love supporting family owned business and people that know what food should taste like.  Definately will.be back for a sit down meal when this is all over!</review>

Under new ownership again (as in not even a month new) but we had a wonderful visit. We stayed at the campground adjacent and ended up visiting every day. < name>
Thomas Eller<//name>
<rating>5</rating><Date>1569900035945</Date>< pics>

<name>Stu Warford< /name>< rate>
5< /rate>
<gmap_id>0x80e99b9a0df46c47:0xf626c13e4e818d87< /gmap_id>< Review>
Did a day road trip from Thousand Oaks to this place a few days ago.  Beautiful drive up through the mountains.  Although we're in August, the hills are still green and lovely.  Passed deer on the way up.  Got to Camp Scheideck Lodge right at lunch time on a week day.  Wasn't at all sure what to expect, although reviews were positive.  It's right between a set of small houses and a campground.  A small stream runs through the area.

The "lodge" is really a restaurant from what we can tell.  When we got there, there was one customer and one bar waiter.  The lodge has a lot of character and we were ready for lunch.

We (my wife and I) each ordered hamburgers, mine with fries and hers with a salad.  The servings were well presented and plentiful.  Not only did they look good, but they tasted excellent.  We were pleasantly surprised.

While we were eating, a couple of "regulars" came in and ordered as well.  The staff were very friendly with the regulars and with us as well.  While eating we asked several questions about the area, the campground, and a nearby trail.   The staff really were hospitable and showed interest in us and our questions.

By the time we left, we were well satisfied and felt really welcomed.  This proved to be a gem, and we've added it to our list of places to return to.< /Review>
